<TITLE> UK car registrations soar in July-SMMT </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 LONDON, Aug 6 (bdnews24.com/Reuters) - British new car registrations rose 4.9 percent in July from a year ago to 176,277 units, the Society of Motor Manufacturers said on Monday, in a sign that consumers are taking higher interest rates in their stride. That was the biggest gain since January, but was helped by a 4.1 percent fall in registrations last July, SMMT said. It revised up its forecast for car registrations this year by 20,000 units to 2.355 million units. Monday's data showed registrations of cars for private customers rose 2.8 percent on the year to 70,258 units, while business car registrations gained 11.3 percent to 11,268 units. "Continued strength heading into the second half of the year suggests that the rises in interest rates over the past 12 months is yet to hit consumer demand for big-ticket items," said Peter Newland, economist at Lehman Brothers. The Bank of England has raised rates five times since last August to 5.75 percent and many analysts expect it to hike borrowing costs at least once more this year. Still, the strength in the car figures looks partly ti be the result of steep declines in the prior year. In July 2006, registrations of private cars were down 9.8 percent on the year and business car regisrations were 9 percent lower, SMMT sa
